{\rtf1\ansi \deff0{\fonttbl{\f8\fswiss Arial;}}\margl1440\margr1200\pgnstart153\sectd\pgnrestart\pgnstarts153\footery1080{\header \pard\plain\qr MYARC ADVANCED BASIC\par }{\footer \pard\plain\qr     VERSION 4.0  DDI SOFTWARE  \chpgn \par }\pard \plain\f8\fs20 PATTERN --Subprogram\tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab PATTERN\par \par \par \par Format\par CALL PATTERN(#sprite-number,character-coed[....])\par \par Cross Reference\par CHAR, MAGNIFY, SPRITE\par \par Description\par The PATTERN subprogram enables you to change the pattern on one or more sprites.\par \par \tab The sprite-number is a numeric-expression whose value specifies the number of the sprite as assigned in the SPRITE subprogram.\par \par \tab Character-code is a numeric-expression with a value from 0-255, specifying the character number of the character you want to use as the pattern for a sprite.\par \par \qj If you use the MAGNIFY subprogram to change to double-sized sprites, the sprite definition includes the character specified by the character-code and three additional characters (See MAGNIFY.)\par \par Program\par \par The following program illustrates a use of the PATTERN subprogram.\par \par 100 CALL CLEAR\par 110 CALL COLOR(12,16,16)\par 120 FOR A=19 TO 24\par 130 CALL HCHAR(A,1,120,32)\par 140 NEXT A\par 150 A$="0171821214141FFFF4141212119070080E09884848282FFFFF8282848498E000"\par 160 B$="01061820305C4681814246242C180700806018342462428181623A0C0418E000"\par 170 C$="0106182C2446428181465C3020180700806018040C3A6281814262243418E000"\par 180 CALL CHAR(244,A$,248,B$,252,C$)\par 190 CALL SPRITE(#1,244,5,130,1,0,8)\par 200 CALL MAGNIFY(3)\par 210 FOR A=244 TO 252 STEP 4\par 220 CALL PATTERN(#1,A)\par 230 FOR DELAY=1 TO 5 :: NEXT DELAY\par 240 NEXT A\par 250 GOTO 210\par (Press CLEAR to stop program.)\par \par Lines 110 through 140 build a floor.\par \par Lines 150 through 180 define characters 244 through 255.\par \par Line 190 creates a sprite in the shape of a wheel and starts it moving to the right.\par \par Line 200 makes the sprite double-sized.\par \par Lines 210 through 250 make the spokes of the wheel appear to move as the character displayed is changed.\par }
